SECTION 7 \'97 JUDGE PROMPT DESIGN RULES\
================================================================================\
\
All judge LLM calls must follow these rules:\
\
1. System prompt establishes the judge role:\
   "You are an automated QA evaluator for a cold email \
   generation pipeline. You score outputs against explicit \
   rubrics. You output only JSON. You never explain your \
   scores in prose \'97 only in the failures[] and warnings[] \
   arrays. You are strict: partial credit does not exist. \
   A criterion either passes (1) or fails (0)."\
\
2. User prompt includes:\
   - The artifact being judged (full JSON)\
   - The reference artifacts needed for grounding checks\
   - The rubric as a numbered list with explicit pass/fail conditions\
   - The output schema\
\
3. For criteria requiring LLM reasoning (not just string matching):\
   Include 2-3 examples of pass and fail in the prompt.\
   Do not rely on the model's intuition \'97 show it the bar.\
\
4. All judge calls use response_format json_schema strict: true.\
   Judge output schema must be registered in schemas.py as \
   JUDGE_RESULT_SCHEMA.\
\
5. Judge calls have their own trace \'97 do not mix with pipeline traces.\
   Judge traces write to: backend/debug_traces/evals/<run_id>/\
